ed by residents of poor urban neighborhoods in Gary, Indiana. Using census, regional, and local data, and in-depth interviews with the residents of Gary, Sandra L. Barnes argues that many people incur costs resulting from the dual dilemma of being poor and residing in a poor urban area. She explores how factors such as race/ethnicity, neighborhood type, and location influence residents' views, coping strategies, and unconventional approaches toward making ends meet. Well written and accessible, this study of Gary's poor urban neighborhoods offers broad findings that apply to other similarly impoverished Rust Belt cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMinoritieszIndianazGaryxEconomic conditions. 0aMinoritieszIndianazGaryxSocial conditions. 0aPoorzIndianazGary. 0aPovertyxPsychological aspects. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aSociology : Social Stratification. 4aSociology : Urban Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483206/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles